<DOC><DOCNO> AP881003-0312 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-88 1045EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-Iraq-Oil     10-03 0172</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Iraq-Oil,0178</SECOND><HEAD>Iraqi Oil Minister Confers With Saudi Arabian Counterpart</HEAD><DATELINE>JIDDAH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Iraqi oil minister Issam AbdulrahimAl-Chalabi met with his Saudi Arabian counterpart, Hisham Nazer, onMonday to discuss stabilizing the world oil market.   Chalabi told the official Saudi press agency SPA after the briefmeeting that the talks were ``useful.''   SPA quoted the Iraqi minister as reaffirming his country'ssupport for a joint meeting of OPEC's price-monitoring andlong-term strategy committees to control oil production and boostprices.   A joint meeting of the two committees has been called for laterthis month.   Iraq is one of several member states of the Organization ofPetroleum Exporting Countries producing above the quota set by thecartel. Iraq has stressed its need for higher oil revenues to helpfinance reconstruction schemes following its 8-year-old war withIran.   Chalabi recently has visited the other Gulf Arab states that aremembers of OPEC, including Kuwait, Qatar and the United ArabEmirates.   Saudi Arabia is the largest exporter in the 13-nation cartel.</TEXT></DOC>